-- Qatar Electricity Nine-Month Profit Advances 16% to 834.4 Million Riyals
-- B y   R o b e r t   T u t t l e
-- 2010-10-20T11:27:55Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-20/qatar-electricity-nine-month-profit-advances-16-to-834-4-million-riyals.html
Qatar Electricity & Water Co., the
third-largest traded utility in the Middle East by revenue,
posted a 20 percent rise in third-quarter profit as new electric
generation capacity boosted revenue.  Net income  for the three months ended Sept. 30 rose to
364.8 million riyals ($100 million) from 304.1 million riyals a
year earlier, the company said in a  statement  on the Qatar
Exchange today. Earnings per share for the quarter increased to
3.64 riyals from 3.04 riyals.  “The company performance is better than expected,” said
 Essam Abd El Alim , an analyst at Cairo-based Naeem Brokerage who
said he forecast a net income of 357 million riyals for the
quarter. “They are expanding, acquiring new stakes.”  Sales gained 27 percent to 944.3 million riyals, the
company said. The increase came after the company started the
first-phase of Ras Girtas in July, adding 1,833 megawatts of
capacity to the Qatari grid. The second phase is scheduled to
start by April. The 2,000-megawatt Mesaieed power plant reached
full output earlier this year.  The company, which is 43 percent  government owned , was
scheduled to complete the acquisition of a majority stake in
Qatari power provider Ras Laffan Energy earlier this month,
increasing its holding in the company to 80 percent from 25
percent, Chief Executive Officer  Fahad al-Mohannadi  said in Doha
Oct. 5.  The acquisition “will reflect on the fourth-quarter of
2010,” El Alim said. “In 2011, Ras Girtas will be fully
operational and this will affect their revenue next year.”  Syria, Oman  The company plans projects in Syria and unsuccessfully bid
to construct a plant in Oman. Qatar Electricity may partner with
state-controlled Qatar Petroleum and a local company to build a
plant in India, Al-Arab newspaper reported today.  Qatar is using its natural-gas reserves, the third-largest
in the world, to develop industries and raise its power
generation capacity to about 9,000 megawatts by 2012, according
to Qatar National Bank data.  Qatar Electricity  fell 0.5 percent to 114.8 riyals on the
Qatar Exchange today, the fourth daily decline. The stock has
risen 14 percent this year.  To contact the reporter on this story:
